      title: When is the best time to send out a W9 to a vendor to determine if they need a 1099?,
      description: When is the best time to send out a W9 to a vendor to determine if they need a 1099?nnKruze’s tax team helps hundreds of startups cumulatively save millions on their taxes every year - even unprofitable startups can benefit from tax credits. See how much a tax return might cost your company at https://kruzeconsulting.com/startup_calculators/how-much-does-a-startup-tax-return-costnnHey, its Scott Orn at Kruze Consulting. And today, were talking about whens the right time to send a W9 to a vendor, so you can figure out if you need to give them a 1099 or not? 

So lets start really slow here. A W9 is a taxpayer information form thats on the IRS website. Technically, you should send this to all of your vendors. But really, youre just worried about the vendors that are independent contractors, sole member LLCs, partnerships, folks like that. You dont have to worry about S corps or C corps. 

So those folks that need a 1099 to basically state what you paid that vendor during the year on a cash basis, so that they can fill out their taxes. The IRS wants them to get a form so they can fill out their taxes. But also, the IRS wants to get that form themselves so they know what that person should be paying in taxes. So theres definitely a giant cross check happening here, where when that contractor fills out their income tax form, the IRS is checking to see what you paid them and what they actually declared. So thats why 1099s are done. 

Now 1099s are due every January 31st. And so if you dont do those, its a really big deal. Youll get fined, I think its like $1,000 or $2,000 per 1099 not filed. It may even be $10,000. Its a really big number. So you really wanna do this. So when are the best times of the year to send out that W9 so that you can determine whether the vendor gets a 1099 or not? nnSo the first one is, I like to send it out right away when you start working with them. Like when youre signing the contract, its nice to kinda bundle that into the contract, or right before you pay the vendor, especially contractors. Sometimes contractors are disorganized. Theyre a little harder to reach throughout the year, and so if you can get that information right away, thats always helpful. Store it in a really safe place. nnBut sometimes its kinda like, thats not really a scalable process to stop what youre doing all the time and send the W9. So the other alternative is to do it at the end of the year or right in January, when youre preparing all your 1099s. So and that, the cool thing about that is that allows you to run a giant batch process. And so its very, very efficient with your time. And also, youve just determined, youve closed your books for the year. So you know exactly what you paid this person on a cash basis. So it makes filling out the 1099, after you get the W9 a lot easier. 

So I would either do it right away, before you actually pay that vendor. Or do it in January, so you can do it in bulk and handle all of your vendors at the same time. The nice thing is using a tool that kinda hides the social security number is actually really important. You do not want a bunch of social security numbers flying back and forth in your email inbox, or in documents in your email inbox. You wanna really minimize that. Thats just kind of a threat and its liability you dont really wanna take. nnSo we really like using web tools like Track1099 to handle that stuff because they mask all the social security numbers. So again remember, you need to fill out 1099s every year for all your contractors, partnerships, sole member LLCs that you paid throughout the year. Youre gonna do it on a cash basis. 

And you need to get those filed before January 31st. So its really important to know the tax status of all those vendors, so that you can send those 1099s out when its time. Hope that helps, thanks.
